  "meta": {
    "title": "Paul Ricoeur",
    "description": "Paul Ricoeur (1913-2005) is a distinguished French philosopher whose work has been widely translated and discussed across the world. In addition to his academic work, his public presence as a social and political commentator, particularly in France, led to a square in Paris being named in his honor on the centenary of his birth in 2013. Over the course of his long career he wrote on a broad range of issues and engaged many of the leading figures of his time. In addition to publishing more than 30 books, Ricoeur published more than 700 articles in French, many of which have been translated into English. Most of his articles in French have been made available online under the auspices of the Ricoeur Archive in Paris. A major theme that runs through Ricoeur's writings is that of a philosophical anthropology. Ricoeur came to formulate this in terms of the \"capable human being\", which refers to the fundamental capabilities and vulnerabilities that human beings display in the activities that make up their lives and enable them to engage in responsible human action. Though the accent is always on the possibility of understanding human beings as agents responsible for their actions, Ricoeur consistently rejects any claim that the self is immediately transparent to itself or fully master of itself. Self-knowledge only comes through the experience of our relation to the world and of our life with and among others. But if that is the case, the puzzle is to explain to what extent, if at all, the self can be held accountable for its own thoughts and deeds. In the course of developing his anthropology of the capable human being, Ricoeur made several major methodological shifts, partly in response to changes in his intellectual setting, sometimes in ways that challenged his own approach, and sometimes in response to questions that had arisen in his published work or that had not yet been adequately treated there. His early academic training was in the tradition of French reflexive philosophy, a tradition that seeks to understand how the \"I\" comes to be aware of its thoughts and actions starting from the lived experience of reflexive consciousness, our being aware of ourselves as existing, thinking, and acting. This focus on reflexive consciousness played a role in organizing Ricoeur's thinking. His first major publications after World War II, drew both from the French tradition of reflexive philosophy and from existential phenomenology, reflecting his study of Husserl, which had begun prior to World War II, as well as of Karl Jaspers, Gabriel Marcel, Jean-Paul Sartre, and Maurice Merleau-Ponty. By 1960, however, Ricoeur had concluded that to study human reality properly, particularly given the existence of evil, he had to supplement direct phenomenological description with the hermeneutic work of interpretation. This shift led to an increasing focus on a theory of interpretation that could be grafted on to phenomenology, an approach which he characterized as hermeneutic phenomenology. For a hermeneutic phenomenology, meaning arises in and through our use of language to talk about our lived experience. While philosophical language and the categories it uses aspire for clear and univocal concepts, natural language is polysemic; it can have more than one meaning, more than one translation, so most uses of language call for interpretation. He took up this insight through the philosophy of discourse that he developed on the basis of the increased emphasis on language in his philosophy. This hermeneutic or linguistic turn in Ricoeur's thought did not require him to disavow the basic results of his earlier investigations, however it did enable him to see more clearly its broader implications. It led to an increasing emphasis on the fact that we live in time and in history. His late writings also reflect a greater concern for questions of ethics at the individual as well as the societal and political levels, leading to his essays on the idea of the just and his last book on the possibility of mutual recognition and states of peace.",
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "dateCreated": "2026-03-22T05:33:15.763Z",
    "dateModified": "2026-03-22T05:33:15.763Z",
    "datePublished": "2002-11-10T13:00:00.000Z",
    "keywords": [
      "action",
      "gadamer",
      "hermeneutics",
      "identity",
      "kant",
      "logic action"
    ]
  },
  "problemSolved": {
    "statement": "Paul Ricoeur (1913-2005) is a distinguished French philosopher whose work has been widely translated and discussed across the world. In addition to his academic work, his public presence as a social and political commentator, particularly in France, led to a square in Paris being named in his honor on the centenary of his birth in 2013. Over the course of his long career he wrote on a broad range of issues and engaged many of the leading figures of his time. In addition to publishing more than 30 books, Ricoeur published more than 700 articles in French, many of which have been translated into English. Most of his articles in French have been made available online under the auspices of the Ricoeur Archive in Paris. A major theme that runs through Ricoeur's writings is that of a philosophical anthropology. Ricoeur came to formulate this in terms of the \"capable human being\", which refers to the fundamental capabilities and vulnerabilities that human beings display in the activities that make up their lives and enable them to engage in responsible human action. Though the accent is always on the possibility of understanding human beings as agents responsible for their actions, Ricoeur consistently rejects any claim that the self is immediately transparent to itself or fully master of itself. Self-knowledge only comes through the experience of our relation to the world and of our life with and among others. But if that is the case, the puzzle is to explain to what extent, if at all, the self can be held accountable for its own thoughts and deeds. In the course of developing his anthropology of the capable human being, Ricoeur made several major methodological shifts, partly in response to changes in his intellectual setting, sometimes in ways that challenged his own approach, and sometimes in response to questions that had arisen in his published work or that had not yet been adequately treated there. His early academic training was in the tradition of French reflexive philosophy, a tradition that seeks to understand how the \"I\" comes to be aware of its thoughts and actions starting from the lived experience of reflexive consciousness, our being aware of ourselves as existing, thinking, and acting. This focus on reflexive consciousness played a role in organizing Ricoeur's thinking. His first major publications after World War II, drew both from the French tradition of reflexive philosophy and from existential phenomenology, reflecting his study of Husserl, which had begun prior to World War II, as well as of Karl Jaspers, Gabriel Marcel, Jean-Paul Sartre, and Maurice Merleau-Ponty. By 1960, however, Ricoeur had concluded that to study human reality properly, particularly given the existence of evil, he had to supplement direct phenomenological description with the hermeneutic work of interpretation. This shift led to an increasing focus on a theory of interpretation that could be grafted on to phenomenology, an approach which he characterized as hermeneutic phenomenology. For a hermeneutic phenomenology, meaning arises in and through our use of language to talk about our lived experience. While philosophical language and the categories it uses aspire for clear and univocal concepts, natural language is polysemic; it can have more than one meaning, more than one translation, so most uses of language call for interpretation. He took up this insight through the philosophy of discourse that he developed on the basis of the increased emphasis on language in his philosophy. This hermeneutic or linguistic turn in Ricoeur's thought did not require him to disavow the basic results of his earlier investigations, however it did enable him to see more clearly its broader implications. It led to an increasing emphasis on the fact that we live in time and in history. His late writings also reflect a greater concern for questions of ethics at the individual as well as the societal and political levels, leading to his essays on the idea of the just and his last book on the possibility of mutual recognition and states of peace.",
